Text.Value: Hard for you to reward me from the bottom of the ocean.
Unfortunately, I strayed too close. I was captured and transported to the prison in which you found me.
Based on my observations, I have selected certain items I believe will be useful in fighting your cause.
Now that you mention it, saving you was a lot of effort...
My colleagues here are grateful you came to my rescue. Though I regret that my investigations ended in such failure.
My meeting with you led me to a most unsettling conclusion. That my kind had begun to exert influence through this 'Cult of the Absolute.'
Such violence has no place here. The Society is an institution that aims to bring about peace. Not destruction.
You did this? Unacceptable.
It is what Blurg would have wanted.
I will return to the Underdark alone. My research there may yet help its inhabitants, even without the Society's help.
Blurgh and I have consulted on the matter of your reward. Your efforts require some recognition.
Blurg... my loyal friend. I will not find the likes of his mind and curiosity again.
I did not expect that mine would be the life you chose to save.
What will you do now?
Your inclination to generosity is an admirable quality. One I wish to reciprocate.
You tricked me. I cannot abide trickery.
Indeed. Once a reaction has been set in motion, it is difficult to prevent its completion.
No need. You've lost too much here already.
I'd no idea your expectations of me were so low.
Do not think me ungrateful. I am pleased at my continued existence.
You tried to save me once. Only fair that I repay the favour.
I didn't care who 'deserved' to be saved. You have the most to offer me.
The hostages meant nothing to me.
I hope they help you to avoid the fate shared by my colleagues.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Mindmeld. Omeluum hands reward to player (unseen)

Text.Value: Still, I feel a heaviness within me. Ravengard's death will destabilise Baldur's Gate. It may adapt, or it may perish. But it will undoubtedly be transformed.
You found me at the bottom of the harbour. No doubt you will track them down with ease.
I would never have left you behind. I rather like you.
I knew my imprisonment was of my own making. I therefore believed it best for you to save those who invited no such consequence.
That you also saved me was unexpected.
Because hope is important to your kind. Given enough of it, I believed you would not give up on finding the explanation for your tadpole's stasis.
Why were you down there in the first place?
I must agree. I feel a surprising heaviness within me. But it will pass, I am sure.
That's legitimate - my master used similar conceptual tools to focus my mind during training.
Ah. Then you did not act so impulsively as I. And your assumption was not an unfounded one.
Indeed. It is sometimes necessary to divert the unformed mind from distractions that lead thinking away from the path of truth.
Still, I feel a heaviness within me, that my life alone should be worth the loss of so many others. Such extinctions are... regrettable.
Then you would keep our equation balanced. A logical approach.
I could have been killed!
I do not share my kind's opinions on the value of other living beings. I would have seen them all saved, if I could.
As was to be expected. It was only a temporary measure, but one I believed might give you time to find a genuine explanation for your tadpole's stasis.
I felt illithid interference would not be conducive to this plane's survival. I sought out other infected individuals to ascertain the truth of my hypothesis.
It is... pleasurable to see you. Your intervention within the cult's underwater complex was a timely one.
They were innocents, whereas I brought my fate upon myself.
Search at your leisure. I must prepare for my return to the Underdark.
I believed my life to be of the least value in the equation. But I am grateful to have it, as is the Society.
This city is no place for the peaceful pursuit of knowledge. I am... disappointed.
Now I am able to provide more tangible means of assisting in your continued survival.
I take it you came here to seek a reward for my rescue?
I am glad my carelessness did not cost the life of Duke Ravengard.
Leave.
The ring I gave possessed no real capacity to control the tadpole's influence. I simply wished to give you hope.
You wore it because you believed it helped. Therefore it was helping you. Your belief was the ring's purpose, and it served it well.
I killed your colleagues. I just came to finish the job.
The aid you rendered to me far outweighs that which I provided in the Underdark.
So I've been wearing that ring for nothing?
Gratitude won't keep a roof over my head...
Welcome to the Society of Brilliance.
It is... pleasurable to see you. Your intervention within the cult's underwater complex was a timely one.
Once my report is completed, I will return to my usual work in the Underdark. There, at least, I may yet produce worthwhile results.
I am grateful that you were spared such a merciless fate.
The ring possessed no ability to interfere with your tadpole's stasis. You were in no more danger than before. However, I understand you are disappointed.
I am glad my carelessness did not cost the lives of the innocents captives.
I tried to save everyone. It just wasn't possible.
Blurg and I have consulted on the matter of your reward.
Why did you do it?
Don't worry. I realised for myself some time ago.
I understand my gratitude has limited use. You desire more practical compensation for your troubles.
Instead, we have selected a series of items from the Society's vaults.
Ravengard meant nothing to me.
Curious. I appear to have left them elsewhere in the Lodge.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Mindmeld. Omeluum gestures as though about to take out an item. He doesn't find it.

Text.Value: At least there my research may yet do some good, even without the support of the Society.
The Society has deep pockets. I expect to get paid for it.
He meant something to this city. Yet it was I you rescued.
There I saw Gortash and his followers inflict cruelties far beyond any I witnessed in the Underdark.
Such violence has no place here. The Society is an institution that aims to bring about peace. Not destruction.

EditorData.logicalname: Players killed a SoB member - HasMet

Text.Value: A valid hypothesis. One I am glad we do not need to prove.
Given my kind's involvement in creating this evil, it is only right that I do my part in helping you defeat it. Or at least, improving your odds.

EditorData.CinematicNodeContext: Mindmeld. Omeluum hands reward to player (unseen)

Text.Value: A generous attitude. Most would only think to save themselves.
We first thought to ask the denizens of the Underdark for their aid in fighting the cult. Alas, our influence there remains negligible.
Such kinship is unnatural for two such as we are. Yet I too feel some... warmth at your presence.
I too feel some... warmth at your presence.
It is best I do not interfere further with events on the surface. I will return to my research - it has been neglected long enough.
It was not a judgement on your abilities. It was simply the result of my calculations, given the likely outcomes of such a rescue attempt.
Why were you down there in the first place?

Synopsis: If the player has rescued Omeluum from the Iron Throne, then he is in the Lodge for the Society of Brilliance. He tells the player about the events that led him to be imprisoned on the throne, reflects on the outcomes of the rescue (whether the other hostages/Duke Ravengard were saved), and provides them with a reward for his rescue.
